Build a GraphQL API
Tutorial

Build a GraphQL API

4 steps

In this tutorial, we will leverage the prowess of Cody to expand off the GraphQL bounty challenge by adding more endpoints to the GraphQL API. This API will seamlessly wrap multiple endpoints from Etherscan, providing a consolidated interface to track the pivotal metrics of the Ethereum network.

The focal point of this tutorial will be the Chat feature of Cody, a tool specifically designed to streamline and enhance the development experience for developers. Join us on this thrilling journey as we redefine how we interact with Ethereum data!

Let’s Begin! 🤖
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

  • There are no pre-requisites in this tutorial

Learning Outcomes

By the end of this tutorial, you will be able to:

  • Describe how GraphQL works
  • Create your Etherscan API Key
  • Introduce additional Etherscan API endpoints to GraphQL API
  • Run and Query Apollo Server

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 4

  • Step 1: Application Setup

    To expand the GraphQL API that was initially developed involving Etherscan APIs, we will focus on enhancing functionality by incorporating additional endpoints to our GraphQL API!

    By incorporating additional endpoints, we aim to offer a holistic view of the key metrics of the Ethereum network through simple queries to a single GraphQL API endpoint. To further enhance our development journey, we will also integrate the Cody Chat feature, ensuring a smoother and more streamlined development experience.

    Getting Started

    Head over to the GitHub Repository and run the following command to clone the GitHub repository.

    ⚠️ Note: Ensure that you run the following command on the cody_ai directory

    git clone https://github.com/clement-stackup/graphql_etherscan.git

    Next, proceed to open the application on VSCode where you should observe the following as shown below.

    Proceed to run the following command to install the necessary libraries and dependencies.

    npm install

    Exploring the Code Repository with Cody

    Next, we will be prompting Cody to dissect the GitHub repository to provide a simple explanation of the GitHub repository that we have just cloned

    For learners that did not participate in the previous GraphQL campaign or bounty, Cody Chat is a seamless feature that provides a concise overview of the GitHub repository to give you more context about the codebase!

    To get started, click on the “Cody Extension” on VSCode.

    Next, proceed to enter the prompt ”What does this GitHub repository do?” and you should observe Cody’s response as observed below!

    How intuitive was that?

    In mere moments, developers gain instant clarity on a GitHub repository, which invariably facilitates a smoother and more streamlined development experience! We will delve deeper into the functionalities of Cody Chat in the upcoming steps!

  • Step 2: Create Etherscan API Key

    Before diving into the addition of more endpoints to our GraphQL API, it's essential to configure our environment variables, primarily creating an Etherscan API key.

    Under the graphql_etherscan directory, proceed to create a .env file and initialize the Etherscan API environment variable as shown below!

    To locate your Etherscan API key, head over to Etherscan. Next, proceed to login to your Etherscan account and if you currently do not have an Etherscan account, do create an account!

    Once you have logged in, hover over your profile on the top right corner and click on “API Keys” as shown below.

    If you do not have an existing Etherscan API key, proceed to click “Add” to create your very first API key otherwise if you have an existing API key, proceed to copy your API Key Token value and paste it to the .env file!

    With that, we have successfully configured our environment variable! Up next, we will dive into incorporating more Etherscan API endpoints that reflect the key metrics of the Ethereum network to our GraphQL API!

  • Step 3: Write Etherscan API Endpoints

    In this step, we will be expanding our existing GraphQL API by adding two more Etherscan API endpoints to complement our current endpoint.

    Current GraphQL Endpoints

    • Fetch Ether Balance for Vitalik's Address
    • Fetch Total Supply of Ether

    New Additions

    • Fetch Latest Price of Ethereum
    • Fetch Estimation of Confirmation Time

    Through these additions, we aim to elevate our GraphQL API to not only provide the current Ethereum price but also offer an estimated timeframe for a transaction's confirmation on the Ethereum network.

    Write API Endpoints

    To begin, head over to the datasource/ethDataSource.js file

    Under the comment //Paste Code Here For New Endpoints, proceed to copy the following code snippet and paste it below the comment.

    async getLatestEthereumPrice() {
    return this.get(
      `?module=stats&action=ethprice&apikey=${process.env.ETHERSCAN_API}`
    );
  }

  async getBlockConfirmationTime() {
    return this.get(
      `?module=gastracker&action=gasestimate&gasprice=2000000000&apikey=${process.env.ETHERSCAN_API}`
    );
  }
    JavaScript

    Here’s how your datasource/ethDataSource.js file should look like!

    With our datasource configured, next head over to the schema.graphql file!

    Proceed to replace the current GraphQL schema with the following code snippet.

    type Query {
  getEthByAddress: ETH_RESULT!
  getTotalSupplyEth: ETH_RESULT!
  getEthPrice: ETH_PRICE!
  getEstimationTimePerTransaction: ETH_RESULT!
}

"""
List down all fields returned from provided APIs
"""
type ETH_RESULT {
  status: String!
  message: String!
  result: String!
}

type ETH_PRICE {
  status: String!
  message: String!
  result: ETH_PRICE_RESULT!
}

type ETH_PRICE_RESULT {
  ethbtc: String!
  ethbtc_timestamp: String!
  ethusd: String!
  ethusd_timestamp: String!
}
    GraphQL

    Here’s how your schema.graphql file should look like!

    With our schema configured, next head over to the index.js file!

    Proceed to copy the following code snippet and paste it below the comment //Paste Code for New Resolver Functions.

    getEthPrice: (root, _args, { dataSources }) =>
dataSources.ethDataSource.getLatestEthereumPrice(),
getEstimationTimePerTransaction: (root, _args, { dataSources }) =>
dataSources.ethDataSource.getBlockConfirmationTime(),
    JavaScript

    Here’s how your index.js file should look like!

    Introducing Cody In Line Comments

    Before we run our server, let’s run our code through Cody to explain the core functionalities of the resolver functions in the index.js file!

    To begin, proceed to highlight the index.js code snippets, and click on the “+” icon as shown below.

    Proceed to enter the code prompt - “What does this code do?” and click “Ask Cody”. 

    Upon completion, Cody will generate a comprehensive description detailing how our Apollo Server is structured and highlighting the roles of the various resolver functions as shown below.

    With a better understanding of the Apollo Server structure along with the GraphQL API, we are now ready to run our server!

    Head over to your terminal and run the following command to initialize the Apollo server!

    node index.js

    You should observe the following console output indicating that your server is initialized successfully!

    On your browser, head over to localhost:9000 and you should observe the following!

    Click on “Query your server” and you should be directed to the Apollo playground.

    Proceed to copy the following code snippet to populate the query fields! 

    query {
  getEthByAddress {
    message
    result
  }
  getTotalSupplyEth {
    message
    result
  }
  getEthPrice {
    message
    result {
      ethbtc
      ethusd
      ethusd_timestamp
    }
  }
  getEstimationTimePerTransaction {
    message
    result
  }
}
    GraphQL

    Next, click on “Run”.

    You should observe the following JSON response from your Apollo Server indicating a successful request to your GraphQL API as shown below.

    With that, we are done with this tutorial!

    In the next tutorial, we will deploy our GraphQL API to a GitHub Repository and make it public for others to query your GraphQL API endpoint!
